<task id="installation-instructions-linux-server" >
    <title>Unix / Linux Server Configuration</title>
  <prolog>
    <metadata>
      <keywords><indexterm>Installation
                    <indexterm>multiple instances (Unix / Linux server)</indexterm></indexterm></keywords>
    </metadata>
  </prolog>
    <taskbody>
        <context>
            <p>To install <ph keyref="product"/> on a Unix / Linux server:</p>
        </context>
        <steps>
            <step>
                <cmd>Install <ph keyref="product"/> on the server and
          <?oxy_comment_start author="Mark" timestamp="20140730T172720-0400" comment="Would this not apply equally to the regular install. Is there any reason that it would not be executable?"?>make
          sure the <ph keyref="executableInstallLinux"/> script is executable and the installation
          directory is in the PATH of the users that need to use the
          application.<?oxy_comment_end?></cmd>
            </step>
            <step>
        <cmd>If you need to run multiple instances of the <ph keyref="product"/>, make sure you add
          the <varname>-Dcom.oxygenxml.MultipleInstances=true</varname> parameter in the startup
          script.<?oxy_comment_start author="Mark" timestamp="20140730T172731-0400" comment="Need and example to show how this is done."?></cmd>
        <?oxy_comment_end?>
      </step>
      <step>
        <cmd>Make sure you allocate sufficient memory to <ph keyref="product"/> by setting an
          appropriate value for the <codeph>-Xmx</codeph> parameter in the <filepath>.sh</filepath>
          startup script.
          <?oxy_comment_start author="Mark" timestamp="20140730T172740-0400" comment="Need an example and some information on how to determine if you need more memory and how much you may need."?></cmd>
        <?oxy_comment_end?>
      </step>
            <step>
        <cmd>Make sure the X server processes located on the workstations allow connections from the
          server host. For this, use the <keyword>xhost</keyword> command.
          <?oxy_comment_start author="Mark" timestamp="20140730T172755-0400" comment="This seems to say too much or too little. If we assume the reader is an experience Linux admin, wouldn&apos;t they know this. And if they are not, this is not enough information for them to act on."?></cmd>
        <?oxy_comment_end?>
      </step>
            <step>
                <cmd><?oxy_comment_start author="Mark" timestamp="20140922T132912-0400" comment="I&apos;m assuming this is the action  to take. Previously there was no verb in this sentence."?>Start<?oxy_comment_end?>
          <?oxy_comment_start author="Mark" timestamp="20140730T172809-0400" comment="This seems to be a separate procedure for someone to run Oxygen from the server. If so, it should be separate and we one for NT server as well. "?>telnet<?oxy_comment_end?>
          (or ssh) on the server host.</cmd>
            </step>
            <step>
                <cmd>Start an xterm process, with the <b>display</b> parameter set on the current
          workstation. For example: <cmdname>xterm -display workstationip:0.0</cmdname>.</cmd>
            </step>
            <step>
                <cmd>Start <ph keyref="product"/> by typing <ph product="editor">
            <cmdname>oxygen.sh</cmdname>
          </ph>
          <ph product="author">
            <cmdname>oxygenAuthor.sh</cmdname>
          </ph><ph product="developer">
            <cmdname>oxygenDeveloper.sh</cmdname>
          </ph>
          <ph product="svnClient">
            <cmdname>syncroSVNClient.sh</cmdname>
          </ph>.</cmd>
            </step>
        </steps>
    </taskbody>
</task>
